Kaitlyn Lee

Bio

Kaitlyn Lee is a MA/PhD student in Biostatistics at the UC Berkeley mentored by Professor Alejandro Schuler. Her research interests are broadly in causal inference, machine learning, and methods research. She is interested in developing methods to answer real-world questions about health and social policy in a statistically rigorous manner. Her current work focuses on causal inference with continuous treatment variables.

Education

UC Berkeley | Berkeley, CA

PhD in Biostatistics | August 2022 - May 2027 (expected)

MA in Biostatistics | August 2022 - August 2024

Harvard College | Cambridge, MA

AB in Physics with Statistics Secondary | August 2016 - May 2020

Awards and Fellowships

Experience

Cornerstone Research | Analyst | January 2017 - June 2022

Huybers Lab, Harvard University | Research Assistant | May 2020 - December 2020

Publications and Conference Presentations

  • Lee, K. J., Hubbard, A., Schuler, A. (2024). Bridging Binarization: Causal Inference with Dichotomized Continuous Exposures. arXiv:2405.07109. (In Review)
  • Lee, K. J., Hubbard, A., Schuler, A. (2024, May 15). Bridging Binarization: Causal Inference with Dichotomized Continuous Treatments [Poster Session]. American Causal Inference Conference, Seattle, WA.
  • Lee, K. J., Hubbard, A., Schuler, A. (2024, June 20). Bridging Binarization: Causal Inference with Dichotomized Continuous Treatments [Poster Session]. Society of Epidemiological Research Conference, Austin, TX.
  • Gordon, E. R., Trager, M. H., Kwinta, B. D., Stonesifer, C. J., Lee, K. J., Adeuyan, O., … Geskin, L. J. (2024). Maintenance therapy for CTCL: importance for prevention of disease progression. Leukemia & Lymphoma, 1–8. https://doi.org/10.1080/10428194.2024.2376164.
